                        <div id="hl2">
                <h2>WHO says ‘vaccine nationalism’ cannot beat virus</h2>
            </div>
                    </div> <!-- /article headline -->
        <div class="row-fluid">
            
                <div class="span12">                    
                    <div id="rpt">                        
                        BSS/AFP, GENEVA                    </div>  

                </div>   


                        </div>

        <!-- article vote, print, total comments & total read -->
        <div class="row-fluid"> <!-- article details -->
            
                <div class="span12 text-center space_bottom" style="margin-top:10px;">
                    <img alt="WHO says ‘vaccine nationalism’ cannot beat virus" src="./assets/news_images/7568999698787.gif">                    
                                    </div>
                

            <div id="newsDtl">
                 
                  
                                
                <p style="text-align:justify">The World Health Organization on Thursday warned against &ldquo;vaccine nationalism,&rdquo; saying vaccine-hogging richer countries would not be safe coronavirus havens if poor nations remained exposed.</p>                         <div class="visible-desktop" style="width:300px; height: 300px!important; float: left; margin-right:30px;"><div class="row-fluid"><span class="span12"><script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js"></script>
<!-- Ad-300x250 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:inline-block;width:300px;height:250px"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-2779657702599345"
     data-ad-slot="1717548141"></ins>
<script>
     (adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></span></div></div>                        
                        

<p style="text-align:justify">WHO chief Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus said it would be in wealthier nations&rsquo; interests to ensure that any vaccines eventually produced to protect against the new coronavirus were shared globally.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ldquo;Vaccine nationalism is not good, it will not help us,&rdquo; Tedros told the Aspen Security Forum in the United States, via video-link from the WHO&rsquo;s headquarters in Geneva.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ldquo;For the world to recover faster, it has to recover together, because it&rsquo;s a globalised world: the economies are intertwined. Part of the world or a few countries cannot be a safe haven and recover.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ldquo;The damage from COVID-19 could be less when those countries who&hellip; have the funding commit to this.&rdquo;</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">He said the existence of the deadly respiratory disease anywhere put lives and livelihoods at risk everywhere.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ldquo;They are not giving charity to others: they are doing it for themselves, because when the rest of the world recovers and opens up, they also benefit.&rdquo;</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ndash; Race for the vaccine &ndash;</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">The United Nations health agency also said that multiple different types of vaccines would likely be needed to combat COVID-19.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">Twenty-six candidate vaccines are in various stages of being tested on humans, with six having reached Phase 3 wider levels of clinical trials.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ldquo;Phase 3 doesn&rsquo;t mean nearly there,&rdquo; explained the WHO&rsquo;s emergencies director Michael Ryan.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ldquo;Phase 3 means this is the first time this vaccine has been put into the general population, into otherwise healthy individuals, to see if the vaccine will protect them against natural infection.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ldquo;We&rsquo;ve got a good range of products across a number of different platforms, across a number of different countries,&rdquo; he said of the leading candidate vaccines, which use different methods to provide immunity.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">However, &ldquo;there&rsquo;s no guarantee that any of these six will give us the answer &mdash; and we probably will need more than one vaccine to do this job.&rdquo;</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ndash; &lsquo;Americas remain epicentre&rsquo; &ndash;</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">The novel coronavirus has killed over 708,000 people and infected more than 18.8 million since the outbreak emerged in China last December, according to a tally from official sources compiled by AFP.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ldquo;The Americas remain the current epicentre of the virus and have been particularly hit hard,&rdquo; said Tedros, with the United States, Brazil and Mexico suffering the most deaths.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">Asked about the virus raging in the Americas, Ryan said no country had always found all the right answers, and a vast expansion of the public health workforce was required.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ldquo;We need to take a step back, we need to look at the problem again and we need to go at the problem again,&rdquo; he said.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ldquo;That requires strong, sustained and trusted leadership.&rdquo;</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">US President Donald Trump has accused the WHO of being a &ldquo;puppet&rdquo; of China and mismanaging its handling of the global pandemic.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">Washington last month handed in its 12-month notice to leave the WHO, depriving the UN organisation of its biggest donor.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">Tedros said the biggest &ldquo;problem&rdquo; with the US departure was &ldquo;not about the money&rdquo; but the fracture in international solidarity in fighting the virus.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ldquo;We hope the US will reconsider its position,&rdquo; he said.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">The Ethiopian former health minister claimed any problems Washington had with the WHO could be resolved without the US leaving.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ldquo;I hope the relationship will return to normal and be a stronger relationship than ever before,&rdquo; he said.</p> 

<p style="text-align:justify">&ldquo;I urge all leaders to choose the path of cooperation&hellip; it&rsquo;s the only choice we have.&rdquo;</p> 

<p style="text-align:right">HM</p> 

<p>&nbsp;</p> 

